    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1918-12-14T14:00:00-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1918-12-14T14:00:00-05:00" n="248"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d248">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">763.72/12555: Telegram</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The Chargé in Serbia</hi> (<persName type="from">
                        <hi rend="italic">Dodge</hi>
                    </persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the <gloss type="to">Acting Secretary of
                            State</gloss>
                    </hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Belgrade</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1918-12-14T20:00:00+01:00"
                            >December 14, 1918—8 p.m.</date>
                        <lb/> [Received December 17—10:09 p.m.]</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>Assistant Minister for Foreign Affairs spoke to me today of Italian attitude,
                    stating confidentially that to him personally complaints to Italy and seeming
                    indifference to Yugo-Slav interests of Allies were inexplicable, and that while
                    Servia will do everything to restrain her troops and greatly irritated Dalmatian
                    population an incident might occur at any moment involving the most far-reaching
                    consequence. Italy seemed bent upon provoking such an incident with a view to
                    alienating Servia from her Allies. He referred, among other matters, especially
                    to irritation caused by Yugo-Slav ships being obliged to fly Italian colors.
                    They would willingly fly any other Allied flags.</p>
                <p>Minister’s expression may be considered representative of present prevailing
                    opinion here.</p>
                <p>Italian residents at Zara recently insulted British and Japanese flags, Italian
                    officers present not interfering. Italian divisions Fiume reported increased to
                    three.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Dodge</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
    </text>
